<page xmlns="http://projectmallard.org/1.0/"
      type="topic"
      id="concept-restricted-unlabeled">
  <info>
    <link type="guide" xref="index" group="restricted"/>
    <desc>The difference between &lt;restricted&gt; and &lt;unlabeled&gt;, and why it matters.</desc>
  </info>

  <title>&lt;restricted&gt; vs &lt;unlabeled&gt;</title>

  <p>
    <cmd>umrs-ls</cmd> uses two special group labels for objects whose security context
    cannot be fully verified. They are not interchangeable.
  </p>

  <terms>
    <item>
      <title><code>&lt;restricted&gt;</code></title>
      <p>
        <sys>open()</sys> was <em>denied</em> — either by DAC permissions (e.g., a
        <code>0700</code> or <code>0600</code> directory) or by a MAC policy decision
        (SELinux denied the <sys>open</sys> permission). Because no file descriptor could
        be established, <sys>fgetxattr</sys> cannot be called. The security label at the
        inode level is <em>unverifiable</em> for the current subject. The tool records
        what it can see from the directory stream — the name and nothing more.
      </p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title><code>&lt;unlabeled&gt;</code></title>
      <p>
        <sys>open()</sys> <em>succeeded</em> and a valid file descriptor was obtained,
        but <sys>fgetxattr(fd, "security.selinux")</sys> returned <sys>ENODATA</sys>.
        The object is genuinely not labeled. This can occur on filesystems without SELinux
        xattr support, or on objects that were created outside of SELinux policy.
      </p>
    </item>
  </terms>

  <section id="why-it-matters">
    <title>Why this distinction matters</title>

    <p>
      Standard <cmd>ls -Z</cmd> uses <sys>lstat</sys>, a path-based syscall. <sys>lstat</sys>
      asks the kernel: "what is the label for the file at this path?" The kernel resolves
      the path and returns a label string. The calling process never establishes a
      file-descriptor relationship with the object.
    </p>

    <note style="important">
      <p>
        <cmd>ls -Z</cmd> can show a label for an object that the current subject cannot open.
        The label is what the kernel <em>claims</em> is there — it is not verified through
        direct file-descriptor access to the inode. A TOCTOU race (a symlink swap or rename
        between the <sys>lstat</sys> call and any subsequent operation) can cause the path
        and the inode to diverge.
      </p>
    </note>

    <p>
      <cmd>umrs-ls</cmd> does not trust the path string. It attempts to <sys>open()</sys>
      each object to anchor to the physical inode. All subsequent reads —
      <sys>fgetxattr(fd, "security.selinux")</sys>, <sys>ioctl(fd, FSGETXATTR)</sys> —
      operate through that descriptor.
    </p>

    <p>
      If <sys>open()</sys> is denied, the inode is unreachable. The entry is marked
      <code>&lt;restricted&gt;</code> to make the gap visible. The tool does not fall back
      to <sys>lstat</sys> to fill in a label. It does not silently succeed with unverified
      data. Failing visibly is the correct behavior.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="auditor-framing">
    <title>The auditor framing</title>

    <p>
      When <cmd>umrs-ls</cmd> reports <code>&lt;restricted&gt;</code> and
      <cmd>/bin/ls -Z</cmd> reports a label for the same entry, this is not a discrepancy
      between two tools. It is a <em>verification gap</em> made explicit.
    </p>

    <list>
      <item><p><cmd>/bin/ls -Z</cmd> shows a <em>claimed</em> label based on path lookup.</p></item>
      <item><p><cmd>umrs-ls</cmd> reports <code>&lt;restricted&gt;</code> because it cannot establish a <em>verified chain of custody</em> to the inode.</p></item>
    </list>

    <p>
      The label may be accurate. It may also not be. The tool cannot determine which is
      true, so it does not pretend to know. This behavior follows the NSA RTB
      Non-Bypassability principle (RAIN): a security check that can be bypassed by
      withholding a file descriptor is not a check.
    </p>
  </section>
</page>
